Data Reanalysis of Wang et al. (2018)

Kevin Sanchez

4/16/2020

Introduction

Wang et al. (2018) — 17β-estradiol (E2) promotes growth and stability of new dendritic spines via estrogen receptor β pathway in intact mouse cortex

Recent studies have found that altering levels of estradiol (E2), the most potent estrogen, can affect neuronal function in several brain regions like the hippocampus and prefrontal cortex. One potential mechanism is through modulation of dendritic spine density in these brain regions, which can impact advanced cognitive functions like learning and memory. The objective of this paper is to quantify how E2 treatment can alter the growth and removal of these dendritic spines. Additionally, the authors wanted to investigate which of the two estrogen receptors (ERs), ERα and ERβ, are involved in mediating this process. They used the ER agonists α-PPT and β-DPN to enhance the activity of ERα and ERβ, respectively.

Their raw data is stratified into two discrete time periods where they observed changes in dendritic spines: 0-4 days (d4) and 4-8 days (d8). For some analyses, they used the combination of these time periods from 0-8 days (dT). The raw data quantifies the total number of dendritic spines initially observed (d#_total) and the number of spines that were stable, eliminated, or formed after the time period described (d#_stable, d#_elim, d#_form, respectively).

The analyses performed by the authors include descriptive statistics for each of the parameters described above, including the mean, standard deviation, and standard error of the mean. To determine if there were differences between experimental groups, the authors employed a t-test. All of their data were graphed as bar graphs.

In this assignment, I will be replicating most of the descriptive statistics that the authors performed. Using their data comparing dendritic spine characteristics between the control and E2-treated mice, I will redo their t-test and compare it to the authors’ results. Lastly, I will recreate the three graphs from Figure 2 of their paper.

Other studies have demonstrated that treatment with E2 increases spine density; therefore, I would expect to have a higher value of dT_total in the E2 group compared to the WT1 group.

Doing these box plots allows for neat visual comparisons between groups and for observing the variability within groups. Another method of data exploration includes using the package {psych} to determine correlations between several variables. I will first use the select() function of {dplyr} to condense the rawdata data set to include variables looking at dendritic spine characteristics across the 8 day experiment (i.e., dT_total, dT_stable, dT_elim, and dT_form. I will then pass this selected data set through the pairs.panels() function to create the scatter plot matrix of correlation between variables.

library(psych)
## 
## Attaching package: 'psych'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     %+%, alpha
rawdata_select <- select(rawdata, Exp_Group, dT_total, dT_stable, dT_elim, dT_form)
pairs.panels(rawdata_select[],
             smooth = FALSE,
             lm = TRUE,
             method = "pearson",
             hist.col = "#00AFBB",
             density = TRUE,
             ellipses = TRUE
)

From this scatter plot matrix, I can that there is a strong, positive correlation (r=0.97) between the total amount of dendritic spines and the number of stable, persistent spines. Now that I have done some exploratory data analysis, I will replicate some of the authors’ data, repeat their t-tests between experimental groups, and recreate the three graphs from Figure 2 of their paper.

Replications and Reanalysis

To start, I will first reanalyze the describe statistics in Sections 2.2 and 2.3 of the paper. This entails quantifying how E2 treatment affects dendritic spine formation rate, total quantity of spines, and persistent newly formed spines. First, I will determine whether the spine formation rate is different between the WT1 and E2 groups during the 0-4, 4-8, or 0-8 day window. Spine formation rate (SFR) is determined as the number of newly formed spines (d#_form) divided by the the total number of spines (d#_total) multiplied by 100 to obtain the percentage. Below, I calculate the mean and standard error of the mean (i.e., standard deviation divided by the square root of counts) for the two groups at the different time points.

print("SFR (Mean ± SEM) for WT Group Between Days 0-4")
## [1] "SFR (Mean ± SEM) for WT Group Between Days 0-4"
(SFRm_WT_4 <- mean(WT1$d4_form / WT1$d4_total, na.rm = TRUE) * 100)
## [1] 4.617878
(SFRs_WT_4 <- sd((WT1$d4_form / WT1$d4_total) * 100, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(length(WT1$d4_form)))

In the paper, the authors state “the spine formation rate increased significantly four days after E2 treatment (Fig. 2B; spine formation during days 0–4: control, 4.6 ± 0.6%; E2, 6.4 ± 0.5%).” My reanalysis of the SFR from the raw data corroborates the authors’ statement. The mean ± SEM value for SFR_WT_4 and SFR_E2_4 are 4.62 ± 0.58% and 6.44 ± 0.51%, respectively.

Next, I will compare the total dendritic spine count (TSC) between the WT1 and E2 groups across the different time periods. This total spine count is calculated as 100% plus the percentage of newly formed spines (d#_form) minus the percentage of eliminated spines (d#_elim). I have already calculated the percentage of newly formed spines above, but will redo the analysis using the mutate() function from {dplyr} instead of just raw calculations. The additional columns created will be added to a new data set called either WT1m or E2m.

WT1m <- mutate(WT1, "SFR_4" = WT1$d4_form / WT1$d4_total * 100)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "SFR_8" = WT1$d8_form / WT1$d8_total * 100)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "SFR_T" = WT1$dT_form / WT1$dT_total * 100)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "SER_4" = WT1$d4_elim / WT1$d4_total * 100)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "SER_8" = WT1$d8_elim / WT1$d8_total * 100)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "SER_T" = WT1$dT_elim / WT1$dT_total * 100)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "TSC_4" = 100 + WT1m$SFR_4 - WT1m$SER_4)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "TSC_8" = 100 + WT1m$SFR_8 - WT1m$SER_8)
WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "TSC_T" = 100 + WT1m$SFR_T - WT1m$SER_T)

E2m <- mutate(E2, "SFR_4" = E2$d4_form / E2$d4_total * 100)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "SFR_8" = E2$d8_form / E2$d8_total * 100)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "SFR_T" = E2$dT_form / E2$dT_total * 100)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "SER_4" = E2$d4_elim / E2$d4_total * 100)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "SER_8" = E2$d8_elim / E2$d8_total * 100)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "SER_T" = E2$dT_elim / E2$dT_total * 100)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "TSC_4" = 100 + E2m$SFR_4 - E2m$SER_4)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "TSC_8" = 100 + E2m$SFR_8 - E2m$SER_8)
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "TSC_T" = 100 + E2m$SFR_T - E2m$SER_T)

This analysis perfectly matches what is described by the authors. They stated “a significant increase in the total spine number in E2 implanted mice compared to that in control mice (Fig. 2C; total spine number during days 0–4: control, 96.5 ± 0.9%; E2, 100.0 ± 0.5%; total spine number during days 0–8: control, 93.6 ± 1.5%; E2, 98.9 ± 1.2%)”. During days 0-4, I found an average TSC of 96.47 ± 0.87% in the WT1 group and 99.98% ± 0.51% for the E2 group. From days 0-8, I reported an average TSC of 93.59 ± 1.49% and 98.87 ± 1.16% for the WT1 and E2 groups, respectively.

The final descriptive statistic test I will perform will be calculating the persistent newly formed spine ratio (PNFS). This measures the percentage of newly formed spines (previously determined as SFR) that remained and persisted during days 0-4 of the experiment. In our data files, this information can be found under the variable d4_nfs_pers. As before, I will first use the mutate() function and then calculate the average and standard error of the mean.

WT1m <- mutate(WT1m, "PNFS" = WT1m$d4_nfs_pers / WT1m$d4_form * 100)
print("PNFS (Mean ± SEM) for WT Group Between Days 0-4")
## [1] "PNFS (Mean ± SEM) for WT Group Between Days 0-4"
(PNFSm_WT <- mean(WT1m$PNFS, na.rm = TRUE))
## [1] 37.5
(PNFSs_WT <- sd(WT1m$PNFS, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(length(WT1m$PNFS)))
## [1] 8.333333
E2m <- mutate(E2m, "PNFS" = E2m$d4_nfs_pers / E2m$d4_form * 100)
print("PNFS (Mean ± SEM) for E2 Group Between Days 0-4")
## [1] "PNFS (Mean ± SEM) for E2 Group Between Days 0-4"
(PNFSm_E2 <- mean(E2m$PNFS, na.rm = TRUE))
## [1] 68.8476
(PNFSs_E2 <- sd(E2m$PNFS, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(length(E2m$PNFS)))
## [1] 3.874982

From these calculated results, we can see the values very closely match those reported by the authors. In the manuscript, they state that “in the E2 exposure group, the persistent newly formed spine ratio is almost twice as high as that in the control group (Fig. 3C; control, 37.5 ± 9.0%; E2, 68.8 ± 3.9%).” I found that the PNFS was 37.50 ± 8.33% for the control group and 68.85 ± 3.87% for the E2 group.

All of the descriptive statistics calculated thus far make it seem like there is a potential difference in dendritic spine characteristics between the WT1 and E2 groups. To determine whether this is statistically significant, I will conduct a t-test on the spine formation rate, total spine count, and persistent newly formed spine ratio using R.

print("Student's t-Test for Spine Formation Rate from Days 0-4")
## [1] "Student's t-Test for Spine Formation Rate from Days 0-4"
t.test(WT1m$SFR_4, E2m$SFR_4, conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  WT1m$SFR_4 and E2m$SFR_4
## t = -2.3606, df = 13.088, p-value = 0.03442
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -3.4902238 -0.1557774
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  4.617878  6.440878
print("Student's t-Test for Spine Formation Rate from Days 4-8")
## [1] "Student's t-Test for Spine Formation Rate from Days 4-8"
t.test(WT1m$SFR_8, E2m$SFR_8, conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  WT1m$SFR_8 and E2m$SFR_8

## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -2.823783  2.474550
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  4.695104  4.869720
print("Student's t-Test for Spine Formation Rate from Days 0-8")
## [1] "Student's t-Test for Spine Formation Rate from Days 0-8"

When the authors performed a Student’s t-test on their results for the spine formation rate from days 0-4, they got a p-value of 0.034. Performing this same analysis in R led to a p-value of 0.03442, which is consistent with what the authors found. Next, the authors calculated a p-value of 0.006 in comparing the total number of spines from days 0-4 and a p-value of 0.024 from days 0-8. Once again, the results that I obtained by performing the Student’s t-test was identical to that in the paper. I attained a p-value of 0.006139 between days 0-4 and 0.02401 from days 0-8. Lastly, the authors noted a p-value of 0.016 in comparing the persistent newly formed spine ratio from days 0-4. When I conducted this analysis, I got a p-value of 0.01545 that is very similar to what the authors found. Since all of these p-values are under the critical value of 0.05, then it can be stated that these presented results are statistically significant.

My next goal is to recreate the three graphs from Figure 2 of their paper. This image investigates how E2 treatment affects dendritic spine turnover and density during days 0-4, 4-8, and 0-8. In order to create these graphs, I need to create a new data frame that compiles all the values of SER, SFR, and TSC across the different experimental groups and day range. The key function that I use for this is unlist().

Exp_Group <- c(rep("WT", 21), rep("E2", 27))

Now, I will create a function that determines the mean and standard error of the mean for each of the variables that will be plotted. I will call this function data_summary. The output after using this function will be stored in a new data frame (Fig2_###_datsum) that is specific to each of the three variables to be plotted (i.e., SER, SFR, and TSC). The package {ggplot2} will then be used to replicate the graphs in Figure 2 of the paper. I will lay out each panel side-by-side for easy comparison between these graphs.

library(plyr)
## ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
## You have loaded plyr after dplyr - this is likely to cause problems.
## If you need functions from both plyr and dplyr, please load plyr first, then dplyr:
## library(plyr); library(dplyr)
## ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
## 
## Attaching package: 'plyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     arrange, count, desc, failwith, id, mutate, rename, summarise,
##     summarize
data_summary <- function(data, varname, groupnames){
  require(plyr)
  summary_func <- function(x, col){
    c(mean = mean(x[[col]], na.rm = TRUE),
      se = sd(x[[col]], na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(length(x[[col]])))
  }
  data_sum <- ddply(data, groupnames, .fun = summary_func, varname)
  data_sum <- rename(data_sum, c("mean" = varname))
  return(data_sum)
}

Fig2_SER_datsum <- data_summary(Fig2_data, varname = "SER", groupnames = c("Exp_Group", "Day"))
Fig2_SER_datsum$Exp_Group <- factor(Fig2_SER_datsum$Exp_Group, levels = c("WT", "E2"))
Fig2_SER <- ggplot(data = Fig2_SER_datsum, aes(x = Day, y = SER, fill = Exp_Group)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c('#999999','#E69F00')) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c("0-4", "4-8", "0-8")) +
  xlab("") + ylab("Elimination (%)") +
  scale_color_grey() + theme_classic() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = SER - se, ymax = SER + se), width = .2, 
                position = position_dodge(.9)) +
  labs(fill = "Experimental Group") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 15, len = 6)) +
  ggtitle("Effect of E2 Treatment on Dendritic Spine Elimination") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Discussion

In summary, I was able to successfully replicate the descriptive and inferential statistics of Sections 2.2 and 2.3 of the paper while also recreating Figure 2. The technique the authors used to calculate statistical significance in Figure 2 was a Student’s t-test. The statistically significant differences between the WT1 and E2 groups in terms of SER, SFR, and TSC that I found were also consistent with what the authors reported.

There were several limitations that I noticed in the authors’ data. There were several missing values scattered across different groups that are unaccounted for in the paper. Typically, you would not include data points that you don’t have complete data for, especially if no reason is given for this. The authors’ also had a relatively low n count of just 6 for the WT1 group, which can affect the power of their study. Additionally, when I was doing the exploratory data analyses, I noticed that there was a noticeable difference in total dendritic spine count between the WT1 and WT2 groups, even though these animals were exposed to the same exact treatment condition. In fact, a t-test between these two wild-type groups (performed below) had a p-value of 0.1608. This definitely warrants some explanation as to why this difference exists.

t.test(WT1$dT_total, WT2$dT_total)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  WT1$dT_total and WT2$dT_total
## t = -1.5073, df = 10.659, p-value = 0.1608
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -24.835032   4.692175
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  132.5000  142.5714

I think that the authors could have performed a repeated measures ANOVA to determine whether dendritic spine formation and elimination is also affected as a function of time post-E2 treatment. I feel like performing other statistical tests in addition to a Student’s t-test would help strengthen the paper and could lead to interesting discoveries.

Overall, I feel that working on this assignment has really helped strengthen my R skills. Given that this paper is in a similar research field that I am in, I can now see myself being able to use R in my own research and data analysis. I found that the trickiest parts of this data replication assignment was replicating the graphs in Figure 2. This required some reorganization of the raw data file and creation of new data frames that I was unfamiliar with. I also learned a lot about many of the difficult functionalities of {ggplot2} and what makes it such a versatile package.
